{
  "title": "Deploying Command Line Interface (CLI) Tools Using FastAPI with Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide provides a step-by-step process on how to deploy CLI tools using FastAPI in Python 3.12+, extending the functionality of FastAPI beyond web APIs.",

  "key_points": [
    "FastAPI is not only for building web APIs; it can be used to create powerful command line interfaces.",
    "CLI tools are useful for running tasks and scripts outside of a web environment, such as automated tasks or local development utilities.",
    "To leverage FastAPI for CLI tools, you will use the 'uvicorn' ASGI server along with 'click', a popular Python library for creating command line interfaces.",
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\n\
import fastapi\n\
from fastapi import FastAPI, FastAPICommand\n\
from fastapi.contrib.faunadb import FaunaDB\n\
app = FastAPI()\n\
class MyApp(FastAPICommand):\n    description = 'My custom command-line tool using FastAPI'\n    app = app\n\n\
if __name__ == '__main__':\n    MyApp().run()\n```"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\n\
@app.get('/')\ndef home():\n    return {'message': 'Welcome to my CLI tool!'}\n\n\
@app.command()\ndef custom_command():\n    db = FaunaDB(secret='YOUR_FAUNADB_SECRET_KEY')\n    result = db.query(...)\n    return result\n```"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "This guide utilizes Python 3.12+, FastAPI 0.75.0, and click 8.0.4.",
    "For the best experience, ensure you have these versions installed before following this tutorial."
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "While FastAPI is an excellent choice for building CLI tools, it may not be as fully-featured as some other dedicated CLI libraries like Click or Argparse.",
    "However, the advantage of using FastAPI lies in its ease of integration with web APIs and the ability to write reusable code across various interfaces."
  ]
}
